Properties of fields:
1. No mutable, cannot call setter method directly on object.
2. Can create new objects with updated value  by converting builder and then build.
3. Cannot set null, instead need to use clearFieldName.

Data Types:
1. int = int32/Sint32
2. long = int64/Sint64
3. boolean = bool
4. byte[] = byte
- all fields are optional from generated file.

message Car {
  string name = 1;
}

enum BodyStyle {
  unknown = 0; // Default value
  SEDAN = 1;
  COUPE = 2;
}

message Cars {
  repeated Car car = 1;  
}

message Dealer {
  Car car = 1;
  repeated Car cars = 2; // repeated creates coolection for List and Set
  Map<int32, Car> map = 3;
  Map<int32, Cars> listCarsMap = 4;
}  

- Field never has null value but has some default value. So, hasValue() can be used to check if it not default value.

So it is clear that when transferring data in gRPC no field names are getting transferred. Client and the Server only relies on the field numbers for serializing the deserializing.
That is one of the key advantage gained by gRPC to reduce the payload of the transferring data.

Field numbers below 16 are considered “compact” because they require only one byte in the metadata section.

Performance Advantage: When fields have numbers between 1 and 15, they consume less bandwidth, which reduces latency. 
This is particularly advantageous for frequently accessed fields since they benefit from reduced encoding overhead.

Optimized Storage: By keeping essential fields within this range, the overall message size is minimized, leading to better performance for high-throughput systems.

- gRPC always sends the message in order.
- Streaming if multiple messages are coming. Not constant polling.

=> gRPC uses it as a transport protocol, which enhances performance with features like multiplexing, flow control, and header compression. 
